## 4. OOP: Classes Represent Things, Not Procedures
*(SOLID — Single Responsibility Principle)*

### 4a. God Class — the most common AI/junior failure
A class that does everything is a namespace, not an object. Split on reason to change.

```python
# WRONG — UserManager does DB, auth, email, and formatting
class UserManager:
    def get_user(self, user_id: int): ...
    def hash_password(self, password: str): ...
    def send_welcome_email(self, user: User): ...
    def format_display_name(self, user: User): ...

# CORRECT — each class has one reason to change
class UserRepository:
    def get(self, user_id: int) -> User: ...

class PasswordHasher:
    def hash(self, plain: str) -> str: ...

class UserNotifier:
    def send_welcome(self, user: User) -> None: ...
```

### 4b. Anemic Model — data bags with no behavior
Objects should own their logic. If all your methods are in services that pull data from objects and operate on it externally, you have procedural code disguised as OOP.

> **Pydantic models are excluded from this rule.** They are intentional data-transport objects (`team-rules/rules.mdc`). The anemic model antipattern applies to domain/business logic classes — not to Pydantic request/response models or shared data-model packages.

```python
# WRONG — Order has no behavior; OrderService does everything to it
class Order:
    total: float
    status: str

class OrderService:
    def is_eligible_for_refund(self, order: Order) -> bool:
        return order.status == "completed" and order.total > 0

# CORRECT — behavior belongs to the object that owns the data
class Order:
    total: float
    status: str

    def is_eligible_for_refund(self) -> bool:
        return self.status == "completed" and self.total > 0
```

### 4c. Composition over Inheritance
Inherit only when the subclass IS-A parent (Liskov). For reuse of behavior, compose.

```python
# WRONG — inheritance for code reuse, not for IS-A
class EmailSender:
    def send(self, to: str, body: str): ...

class UserNotifier(EmailSender):   # UserNotifier IS NOT an EmailSender
    def notify(self, user: User): ...

# CORRECT — compose the dependency
class UserNotifier:
    def __init__(self, email_sender: EmailSender) -> None:
        self._email_sender = email_sender

    def notify(self, user: User) -> None:
        self._email_sender.send(user.email, self._build_message(user))
```

### 4d. Tell, Don't Ask
*(Martin Fowler)*
Don't ask an object for its data and then make a decision externally. Tell the object to make the decision itself.

```python
# WRONG — asks for data, decides externally
if user.subscription.plan == "premium" and user.subscription.is_active:
    grant_access(user)

# CORRECT — tells the object to evaluate its own state
if user.has_active_premium_subscription():
    grant_access(user)
```

