## 5. Minimal — Write Only What Is Required
*(YAGNI — You Aren't Gonna Need It)*

Speculative code is technical debt with no corresponding asset.
Every abstraction, base class, factory, or configuration option must be justified by a current requirement.

```python
# WRONG — abstract base class for one concrete implementation that will "probably" have siblings
class BasePaymentProcessor(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def process(self): ...

class StripeProcessor(BasePaymentProcessor):
    def process(self): ...

# CORRECT — one implementation, no hierarchy until a second implementation actually exists
class StripeClient:
    def charge(self, order: Order) -> ChargeResult: ...
```

Add the abstraction when you have two concrete implementations. Not before.

