## 6. Guard Clauses Over Nested Conditions
*(Fowler, Replace Nested Conditional with Guard Clauses)*

Nesting hides the happy path. Guard clauses make the exceptional cases exit early, leaving the main logic flat and readable.

```python
# WRONG — reader must track nested state to understand the main path
def process_refund(order: Order) -> None:
    if order is not None:
        if order.status == "completed":
            if order.total > 0:
                # actual logic here, 3 levels deep
                ...

# CORRECT — each precondition exits immediately; main logic is at the top level
def process_refund(order: Order) -> None:
    if order.status != "completed":
        raise InvalidRefundError(f"order {order.id} is not completed")
    if order.total <= 0:
        raise InvalidRefundError(f"order {order.id} has no refundable amount")
    # main logic is flat and immediately visible
    ...
```

